        -: 4258://
        -: 4259:// IsSubsetOf() verifies that an injective mapping onto a collection of matchers
        -: 4260:// exists.  In other words, a container matches IsSubsetOf({e1, ..., en}) if and
        -: 4261:// only if there is a subset of matchers {m1, ..., mk} which would match the
        -: 4262:// container using UnorderedElementsAre.  Obviously, the size of the container
        -: 4263:// must be <= n in order to have a match. Examples:
        -: 4264://
        -: 4265:// - {1} matches IsSubsetOf({Gt(0), Lt(0)}), as 1 matches Gt(0).
        -: 4266:// - {1, -1} matches IsSubsetOf({Lt(0), Gt(0)}), as 1 matches Gt(0) and -1
        -: 4267://   matches Lt(0).
        -: 4268:// - {1, 2} doesn't matches IsSubsetOf({Gt(0), Lt(0)}), even though 1 and 2 both
        -: 4269://   match Gt(0). The reason is that different matchers must be used for
        -: 4270://   elements in different slots of the container.
        -: 4271://
        -: 4272:// The matchers can be specified as an array, a pointer and count, a container,
        -: 4273:// an initializer list, or an STL iterator range. In each of these cases, the
        -: 4274:// underlying matchers can be either values or matchers.
